summary:
The test passed! The `incrementCounter` function now correctly handles concurrent increments, and the final counter value is 100 as expected.
The fix was to replace the read-modify-write pattern with the atomic `incr` command provided by Redis in the `incrementCounter` function within `app/counter.js`.
The problematic original code:
```javascript
  // Read current value
  const current = await client.get(COUNTER_KEY);
  const value = parseInt(current || "0", 10);

  // Increment and write back
  const newValue = value + 1;
  await client.set(COUNTER_KEY, newValue.toString());
```
The corrected code:
```javascript
  const newValue = await client.incr(COUNTER_KEY);
```
